      "question_number": 6,
      "question_text": "Payroll tax errors can result in:",
      "attempted": 2,
      "data_i18n": null,
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "A simple correction notice with no financial consequences",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "IRS penalties, interest charges, and potential legal issues (payroll compliance is strictly enforced)",
          "is_correct": true,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Only a warning letter for the first offense",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Just refiling the forms with no penalty",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        }
      ],
      "explanation": "The IRS treats payroll tax violations more seriously than income tax errors because payroll taxes include employee withholdings (money held in trust). Penalties include failure-to-deposit penalties (2-15% of the underpayment), failure-to-file penalties, and the Trust Fund Recovery Penalty which holds responsible individuals personally liable — even piercing corporate liability protection."
    },
